3. Assassin&#39;s Creed (Xbox 360): 980,000<br />
4. Guitar Hero III: Legends of Rock (PlayStation 2): 967,000<br />
5. Wii Play w/ Remote (Wii): 564,000<br />
6. Mass Effect (Xbox 360): 473,000<br />
7. Call of Duty 4: Modern Warfare (PlayStation 3): 444,000<br />
8. Guitar Hero III: Legends of Rock (Wii): 426,000<br />
9. Halo 3 (Xbox 360): 387,000<br />
10. Assassin&#39;s Creed (PlayStation 3): 377,000</b><br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Wow.  Wii sells nearly a million units for the month!  360 not far behind with 3/4 of a million sold, that&#39;s pretty impressive!<br />
<br />
On the PS3 front...well, hey big guy, you finally outsold your seven-year-old predecessor for the month!  Um...yay?<br />
<br />
Analysts are now proclaiming Nintendo as the number one player in this generation of consoles, with Microsoft not too far behind but solidly trailing.  The Sony is still a "crash n&#39; burn".  This removal of backwards compatibility WILL bite them on the a$$, there are already plenty of complaints in user forums from people who picked up the $399 bundle not aware of the lack of this feature.<br />
<br />
When there are 100 million+ PS2 users, the last thing you want to do is alienate them.  Morons.  Where XBox and Wii are welcoming players from the previous generation with open arms (or heck, ALL previous generations!) and it&#39;s working for them so well, you&#39;d think Sony might have thought this through.  Oh, well.  Maybe they&#39;ll finally feel Big N&#39;s pain of going from leader to dead last within one generation of consoles, how sad.<br />
<br />
One thing I can&#39;t tell--and they didn&#39;t elaborate--is whether these are US-only numbers.  I&#39;m assuming yes. <br><BR><font size=1>09:14 12-14-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#CCCCCC>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#CCCCCC><font class="bfont"><B>Jedi Genius</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#CCCCCC' ><font class="bfont">Have you even played AC?<br />
<br />
The Frontlines demo is terrible. Don&#39;t bother with it.<br />
<br />
Burnout Paradise demo is... disappointing. The graphics are great. The controls are great. The crashes are great. But the free roaming kind of blows, and there&#39;s only a handful of events available in the demo. <br />
<br />
Realism has been cranked up in this game, with the car feeling heavier (but not slower). Going off of jumps usually yields pretty realistic heights (except "Super Jumps" which are ramps marked with flashing lights). The standard traffic all has far more weight to it than in the previous games. Crashes are very realistic, and not the same canned animations like in the old games. If you smash the right front corner of your car into a concrete barrier, that side caves in fairly realistically. <br />
<br />
To begin an event, you drive to a stop light, and then hit Brake + Gas to begin. Where Burnout Revenge had "Burning Lap", this is now replaced with a race to an endpoint within a set amount of time... only you can get there however you wish. So basically you have to learn the streets really well if you want to start doing well in these events. <br />
<br />
Another event was for stunts, where you have to rack up 50,000 points in a set amount of time, only they start you in the an area with no jumps, so you have to know where the jumps are and drive to them. You can boost between jumps to maintain combos and stuff. Pulling off stunts is a matter of finding the right ramps, hitting them at the right speed and angle (especially for a barrel roll), and making sure you land on your wheels. Even a partial crash that doesn&#39;t total your car kills your combo (like if your car rolls after it hits the ground). Pulling off spins going off jumps isn&#39;t very intuitive, although it&#39;s pretty much your only other trick off of jumps besides barrel rolls (which only works off of special jumps designed for barrel rolls). <br />
<br />
There are "Gates Smashed" and "Billboards Smashed" things, where there are a set amount of each and you&#39;re tasked to find them all (I&#39;m assuming for an achievement or car in the actual game), and these can be done in free roam. The gates lead to the hidden paths, and billboards are generally off of big jumps. <br />
<br />
Online is apparently really easy to jump into, you just use the control pad in game to invite people to join or to join random games. I didn&#39;t try this, but apparently it&#39;s implemented fairly well.<br />
<br />
Overall, I&#39;m somewhat disappointed by the open ended structure of the game. It seems like there is less arcade style racing and crashing into rivals in this game, and those were the best parts of the old game. I think it&#39;ll be a questionable purchase for me come January. <br><BR><font size=1>08:17 12-14-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#FFFFFF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>DBMonkeys</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">AC was one of the worst games I have ever seen. <br />
